│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs in BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::computeExtractCost() due   │
│ to an assertion failure: (Idx + EltsPerVector) <= alignTo(NumElts,            │
│ EltsPerVector). This indicates that an index selected for an                  │
│ SK_ExtractSubvector shuffle refers to a starting position such that the       │
│ requested subvector extends past the padded vector boundary. Assertions in    │
│ LLVM generally assume prior logic guarantees their truth; therefore the bug   │
│ lies in index calculation earlier in the function rather than the assertion   │
│ itself.                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The SLP vectorizer is processing horizontal reductions and later tries to     │
│ build vectors from gathered extractelements. In the debug log we see          │
│ MaskSlice = {0,31,-1,-1,-1,-1}, SubMask mutated to {0,7,-1,-1,-1,-1}.         │
│ NumElts=16 (the maximum vector operand length), EltsPerVector=6 (number of    │
│ elements per part), alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector)=18. Indices computed      │
│ become {0,14}. The second index 14 causes the assertion to fire because 14 +  │
│ 6 = 20 > 18. This comes from the lambda CheckPerRegistersShuffle() where      │
│ OffsetReg1 is derived from the minimal index of the second register region    │
│ (31) aligned down to a multiple of EltsPerVector (alignDown(31,6)=30). Then   │
│ OffsetReg1 % NumElts = 14 is pushed directly into Indices (line ~9804)        │
│ without further adjustment. This implicitly assumes that modulo reduction     │
│ yields a valid subvector start for extraction, which is not true when NumElts │
│ is not a multiple of EltsPerVector.                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The computation of the second register extraction start for two-source        │
│ permutation shuffles fails when the vector length (NumElts) is not divisible  │
│ by EltsPerVector. Specifically:                                               │
│ - OffsetReg1 is computed in the full concatenated index space (possibly       │
│ covering two source vectors) and aligned down there.                          │
│ - The subsequent modulo operation (OffsetReg1 % NumElts) maps that to the     │
│ base vector's index space but can land in the tail region where starting      │
│ index + EltsPerVector exceeds the padded size alignTo(NumElts,                │
│ EltsPerVector).                                                               │
│ - No correction/clamping/alignment is performed after the modulo.             │
│ Thus Indices may contain an invalid starting position, leading to the         │
│ assertion firing during cost estimation before any IR transformation occurs.  │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 9791-9805        │
│ (inside CheckPerRegistersShuffle lambda).                                     │
│ Change the code that pushes OffsetReg1 % NumElts into Indices so that the     │
│ extracted subvector index is guaranteed to satisfy the assertion. Replace:    │
│   Indices.push_back(OffsetReg1 % NumElts);                                    │
│ with logic that realigns/clamps the modulo result, e.g.:                      │
│   int SubIdx = OffsetReg1 % NumElts;                                          │
│   unsigned PaddedSize = alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector);                      │
│   // Ensure starting index is on a valid subvector boundary and fits.         │
│   SubIdx = alignDown(SubIdx, (int)EltsPerVector);                             │
│   if (SubIdx + (int)EltsPerVector > (int)PaddedSize)                          │
│     SubIdx = PaddedSize - EltsPerVector; // final valid start                 │
│   Indices.push_back(SubIdx);                                                  │
│ This preserves intent (aligning the second register start) while ensuring     │
│ legality with respect to the padded vector size. It only affects cost         │
│ modeling indices; no functional transformation semantics are changed.         │
│ Optional additional safety (not strictly required): after computing Indices,  │
│ we could assert each satisfies the invariant, but existing assertion later    │
│ already covers it.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Reasoning for edit scope: Lines 9791-9805 encompass the computation of        │
│ OffsetReg1 and current direct push of the modulo result; modifying here       │
│ rectifies index derivation before later use in the for loop over Indices at   │
│ line 9843.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The bug is caused by improper derivation of extraction start indices for      │
│ second source registers when NumElts is not a multiple of EltsPerVector.      │
│ Adjusting the pushed index by aligning down and clamping to the last valid    │
│ starting position prevents generation of an out-of-range index, satisfying    │
│ the existing assertion. This resolves the crash without altering higher-level │
│ vectorization decisions; only cost estimation bookkeeping is corrected.       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
