  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::computeExtractCost() due to an assertion failure:
(Idx + EltsPerVector) <= alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector). This indicates that an
index selected for an SK_ExtractSubvector shuffle refers to a starting position
such that the requested subvector extends past the padded vector boundary.
Assertions in LLVM generally assume prior logic guarantees their truth; therefore
the bug lies in index calculation earlier in the function rather than the
assertion itself.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe SLP vectorizer is processing
horizontal reductions and later tries to build vectors from gathered
extractelements. In the debug log we see MaskSlice = {0,31,-1,-1,-1,-1}, SubMask
mutated to {0,7,-1,-1,-1,-1}. NumElts=16 (the maximum vector operand length),
EltsPerVector=6 (number of elements per part), alignTo(NumElts,
EltsPerVector)=18. Indices computed become {0,14}. The second index 14 causes the
assertion to fire because 14 + 6 = 20 > 18. This comes from the lambda
CheckPerRegistersShuffle() where OffsetReg1 is derived from the minimal index of
the second register region (31) aligned down to a multiple of EltsPerVector
(alignDown(31,6)=30). Then OffsetReg1 % NumElts = 14 is pushed directly into
Indices (line ~9804) without further adjustment. This implicitly assumes that
modulo reduction yields a valid subvector start for extraction, which is not true
when NumElts is not a multiple of EltsPerVector.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe
computation of the second register extraction start for two-source permutation
shuffles fails when the vector length (NumElts) is not divisible by
EltsPerVector. Specifically:\n- OffsetReg1 is computed in the full concatenated
index space (possibly covering two source vectors) and aligned down there.\n- The
subsequent modulo operation (OffsetReg1 % NumElts) maps that to the base vector's
index space but can land in the tail region where starting index + EltsPerVector
exceeds the padded size alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector).\n- No
correction/clamping/alignment is performed after the modulo.\nThus Indices may
contain an invalid starting position, leading to the assertion firing during cost
estimation before any IR transformation occurs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nFile: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 9791-9805
(inside CheckPerRegistersShuffle lambda).\nChange the code that pushes OffsetReg1
% NumElts into Indices so that the extracted subvector index is guaranteed to
satisfy the assertion. Replace:\n  Indices.push_back(OffsetReg1 % NumElts);\nwith
logic that realigns/clamps the modulo result, e.g.:\n  int SubIdx = OffsetReg1 %
NumElts;\n  unsigned PaddedSize = alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector);\n  // Ensure
starting index is on a valid subvector boundary and fits.\n  SubIdx =
alignDown(SubIdx, (int)EltsPerVector);\n  if (SubIdx + (int)EltsPerVector >
(int)PaddedSize)\n    SubIdx = PaddedSize - EltsPerVector; // final valid start\n
Indices.push_back(SubIdx);\nThis preserves intent (aligning the second register
start) while ensuring legality with respect to the padded vector size. It only
affects cost modeling indices; no functional transformation semantics are
changed.\nOptional additional safety (not strictly required): after computing
Indices, we could assert each satisfies the invariant, but existing assertion
later already covers it.\n\nReasoning for edit scope: Lines 9791-9805 encompass
the computation of OffsetReg1 and current direct push of the modulo result;
modifying here rectifies index derivation before later use in the for loop over
Indices at line 9843.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug is caused by improper derivation
of extraction start indices for second source registers when NumElts is not a
multiple of EltsPerVector. Adjusting the pushed index by aligning down and
